babint 15-Nov-18 09:53 AM
I emailed the bong net guys because why not and asked about getting more info about HAM stuff just to see what he recommended and he shot back a very awesome email back and thought i'd share since had some good links and some info about the repeater itself.
Hello, I hope you enjoyed our Net today. We've been doing it about 4yrs now and have a great time with it. If you would like your own number and be able to check-in via the internet, send me a name/ address to send you a card. The 147.435Mhz repeater (we just call it four, three, five) is known for its questionable content, but its a lot of fun. We are kind of the misfits of Amateur radio. Some other radio groups do not like or associate with us, but oh well. Back in the day, and even today on alot of frequencies, The owners do not want you to talk about Religion, Politics, Sex, or anything that might be controversial. Well, 435 has been known as the Free speech repeater for many years, you can talk about anything you would like to on 435 Some old users on this repeater were even brought into court by the FCC for using the F word, The Hams actually won. So you will hear some cursing on our system. Most of us are good friends, but we enjoy mixing it up. Its not very difficult to get an Amateur radio license, there are 3 levels of license, each with its own privileges on the various frequencies. You can get the licenses by taking a written test (no Morse Code is required anymore for ANY of the licenses ) The easiest license , and the one that will let you talk on our system is the Technician License. You need about 17 questions correct out of 25. Its a pretty easy test. Cost is about $15 Testing sites are all around, like at a Denny's restaurant, or community center or such places. You can find testing dates and facilities and everything else about Ham radio on the ARRL Web site. Here is a link http://www.arrl.org/licensing-education-training This guys website has some great study guides that are very straight forward and downloadable. https://www.kb6nu.com/study-guides/ Oh yeah, you can take practice tests online to get ready. Also, www.QRZ.com is another site with good info.
